<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-02-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-02-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="300" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d300">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Choate</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-02-09"><hi rend="italic">February 9,
                                1904</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Choate states that Lord Lansdowne asks whether Manchuria is within
                            the phrase “neutrality of China” and whether it is under <pb facs="0416" n="328" xml:id="pg_328"/> stood that Japan should preclude herself
                            from activity in that province of China in spite of Russia’s occupation
                            and of which the latter might make use as a base of military
                            operations.)</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>